<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-661-420  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 661 420.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDN  June 28 1990 v35 n13A pS62(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Don't expect too much help from Washington; US science advisorAllan Bromley steers clear of &quot;industrial Randamp;D policy.&quot;andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Colborn, Kate.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>US Presidential Asst for Science and Technology and Office ofScience and Technology Policy Dir D. Allan Bromley asserts thatindustry must be more publicly active to promote governmentsupport of science and technology.andP;  He says that a strong'constituency for science and technology' focusing on 'broad,statesmanlike' issues is vital to the effectiveness of UStechnology.andP;  Bromley does not believe that the government shouldbe involved in managing US research and development (Randamp;D), becausethe government does not have wisdom to determine what thesuccessful technologies, industries or firms will be.andP;  He saysthat technology developed by federal laboratories must be moreeffectively disseminated into the commercial world.andP;  Bromleysupports such broad government measures for Randamp;D support asincreased Randamp;D tax credits and antitrust changes to supportcooperative research.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Scientific ResearchResearch and DevelopmentGovernment FundingGovernment Officials.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   D. Allan Bromley. (portrait)Person:    Bromley, D. Allan (commercial policy).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>